      "FeedId": "https://ardalis.com/index.xml",
      "ItemId": "https://ardalis.com/use-timespan-or-specify-units-in-duration-properties-and-parameters/",
      "Title": "Use TimeSpan Or Specify Units In Duration Properties And Parameters",
      "PublishDate": "2025-11-06T09:51:30-05:00",
      "Summary": "<p>A special case of <a href=\"https://deviq.com/code-smells/primitive-obsession-code-smell\">primitive obsession</a> is the use of an <code>int</code> value to describe a span of time. You see this all the time in various APIs, and it&rsquo;s a frequent source of bugs and confusion. Developers are forced to either guess or try to find the documentation that describes what units <code>int timeout</code> or <code>int delay</code> actually uses.</p>\n<p>Having a retry delay of 1 millisecond instead of 1 second, for example, is a huge difference - that&rsquo;s 1000x more load on your system! But so is having a timeout of 1000 seconds (nearly 17 minutes!) instead of 1000 milliseconds (1 second). Either way, it&rsquo;s three orders of magnitude away from the expected and intended behavior, which can lead to production incidents and difficult-to-diagnose bugs.</p>",
      "Content": null,
      "Language": "en-us",
      "Link": "https://ardalis.com/use-timespan-or-specify-units-in-duration-properties-and-parameters/"
    },
