      "Title": "2024 Year In Review",
      "PublishDate": "2025-02-26T00:00:00+00:00",
      "Summary": "<p>Better late than never, as I&rsquo;m writing this in late February 2025&hellip;</p>\n<p>First, here&rsquo;s a few links to past years in review:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2017-in-review\">My 2017 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2018-year-in-review\">My 2018 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2019-year-in-review\">My 2019 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2020-year-in-review\">My 2020 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2021-year-in-review\">My 2021 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2022-year-in-review\">My 2022 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/2023-year-in-review\">My 2022 Year in Review</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://ardalis.com/year-in-review-post-checklist\">My Year in Review Post Checklist</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now on to the various categories&hellip;</p>\n<h2 id=\"blogging-\">Blogging ✍️</h2>\n<p>Blogging continues its slide into obscurity. In 2024 I had just 18 new articles, which is down from 20 in 2023. I think part of the reason for this is that I&rsquo;ve been focusing more on video content. I also tend to get more immediate feedback on video content, even though it&rsquo;s more effort to create, and there are vanity metrics like YouTube subscribers which offer more of a dopamine hit than page views on a blog. In 2023 I had 20 articles so this is a slight decrease.</p>",
      "Content": null,
