      "ItemId": "https://ardalis.com/when-qa-keeps-finding-bugs/",
      "Title": "When QA Keeps Finding Bugs",
      "PublishDate": "2025-02-12T00:00:00+00:00",
      "Summary": "<p>A developer manager recently reached out with a concern: their new QA team member was finding too many bugs, leading to frustration among developers. Overall velocity of the dev team (in terms of features being shipped) was rapidly falling. The question was, how can they reduce the number of issues being kicked back from QA without discouraging the testers from doing their job well?</p>\n<h2 id=\"qa-isnt-the-problem\">QA Isn&rsquo;t the Problem</h2>\n<p>First and foremost, if QA is finding bugs, that means they&rsquo;re doing their job well. The goal shouldn&rsquo;t be to stop QA from finding bugs. The goal should be to reduce the number of bugs that reach QA <em>in the first place</em>. The real issue likely lies upstream in the development process.</p>",
      "Content": null,
      "Language": "en-us",
      "Link": "https://ardalis.com/when-qa-keeps-finding-bugs/"
    },
